Sancho Panza getting diarrhea from the Balm of Fierabras while Don Quixote vomits is such a sublime moment. Two organisms reacting to the same substance in two different ways. Medicinal laxatives and emetics of the old European medicine. Cervantes knew a lot about folk healing...

The real balm of Fierabras was supposed to be the balm used for Christ's body after the crucifixion. The ingredients are wine, rosemary, oil, salt. This is sorta (?) similar to posca, which was possibly the "vinegar" given to Christ on the Cross, which also was used as a laxative

Book of Tobit in the Old Testament Deuterocanon is the only place in the Bible which mentions dogs without a negative connotation, philologists (and even the old Wikipedia article on it) used to say it was an Aryan myth that was somehow included in the texts. Very mysterious imo.

Tobit really is the thinking man's Bible book. Gene Wolfe was very interested in it too, at the angel appearing as a dead ancestor of Tobias, the loyal dog's philological mystery. Significance of burial of the dead. All adventure stories (as BoTNS, LoTR) trace back to it. Sublime
